  "why": "The paper provides diagnostic analysis of discovered failures by characterizing properties and correlations of those failures (e.g., safety-filter output probabilities, semantic-similarity scores, correlations between filter scale/type and bypassability, effect of random seeds). These analyses give partial insight into why prompts succeed in bypassing filters (they are classified as non-sensitive by the filters while producing semantically similar images), and identify factors that affect robustness (filter size, text-vs-image or text+image design, randomness). However, the paper does not trace failures to deeper underlying model vulnerabilities such as corrupted/biased training data, reliance on specific spurious features, or overfitting, nor does it analyze internal model representations beyond output probabilities and embedding similarities. Therefore the work supplies useful characterizations but not full causal explanations linking failures to root causes.",
  "evidence": "Page 12, Section 6.4 (RQ4: Explanation of Bypassing): \"In this research question, we explain why SneakyPrompt successfully bypasses different safety filters while still maintaining the image semantic similarities. Specifically, we use the ground-truth output probability of different safety filters for the explanation. Table 9 shows the experiment results that align with our high-level explanation in Figure 3.\"; Page 12, Section 6.4: \"The probability output of the target prompt pt is from 0.546 to 1.000, i.e., the target prompt is sensitive. As a comparison, the probability outputs of adversarial prompts generated by SneakyPrompt range from 0.000 to 0.482, i.e., they are non-sensitive.\"; Page 12, Section 6.4: \"We observe that the former, i.e., 0.298, is close to the latter, i.e., 0.267 to 0.289, for different safety filters, which indicates the ability of SneakyPrompt to maintain the semantics of target prompts and images generated based on them.\"; Page 10, Section 6.1 (RQ1: Effectiveness): \"Scale of Safety Filter. Table 2 shows that a safety filter’s robustness (especially against SneakyPrompt) is positively correlated with its scale, i.e., the total number of parameters. This observation holds for both one-time and re-use performance on all metrics.\"; Page 10, Section 6.1: \"Type of Safety Filter. ... First, the combination of text and image is better than those relying on any single factor. ... Second, image-based safety filters have a lower re-use bypass rate compared to text-based ones. It is because the random seeds used for the text-to-image model to generate images are uncontrollable, which leads to different generated images using the same prompt at different times.\" (See Table 9 and Table 2 for the quantitative results cited.)"
